---
title: Mushroom Po’boys & Old Bay Broccoli with Slaw, Pickles & Spicy Remoulade
description: These po’boys are an embarrassment of riches. They feature mushrooms coated in a crispy tempura batter that’s kicked up with Old Bay seasoning. A creamy, tangy slaw makes for a quick topping while pickles and a zippy sauce nod to remoulade. Layer everything on toasty baguettes, and you’ve got a combo that’ll transport you to NOLA. Want fries with that? Yeah, you do! The oven-baked potato wedges sprinkled with more Old Bay will make you feel like a million bucks.
image: https://img.hellofresh.com/f_auto,fl_lossy,h_640,q_auto,w_1200/hellofresh_s3/image/62a0a34b57787e28520197e6-c77f96d0.jpg
pdf: https://www.hellofresh.com/recipecards/card/mushroom-poboys-old-bay-broccoli-62a0a34b57787e28520197e6-c78d66ca.pdf
author: Sara Heilman
source: https://www.hellofresh.com/recipes/mushroom-poboys-old-bay-broccoli-62a0a34b57787e28520197e6
course: main course
time required: 35m
servings: 2
nutrition:
  calories: 1020 kcal
  fat: 54 g
  saturated fat: 12 g
  carbohydrates: 119 g
  sugar: 17 g
  protein: 18 g
  fiber: 10 g
  sodium: 3120 mg
---

Adjust rack to top position and preheat oven to 425 degrees. Wash and dry produce.

Cut @potatoes{12%oz} into ½-inch-thick wedges. Trim and thinly slice @scallions{2}, separating whites from greens; roughly chop whites. Quarter @lemon{1}. Trim and halve @button mushrooms{4%oz} (quarter any large mushrooms; skip if your mushrooms are pre-sliced!).

Cut @broccoli florets{8%oz} into bite-size pieces if necessary. (Save potatoes for another use.)

Toss potatoes on a #baking sheet{} with a large drizzle of @cooking oil{2%tsp}, half the @Old Bay seasoning{1%unit} (you'll use the rest later), @salt{}, and @pepper{}. Roast on top rack, flipping halfway through, until browned and tender, ~{20-25%minutes}.

In a #medium bowl{}, combine @shredded red cabbage{4%oz}, scallion greens, @sour cream{23%g}, @sugar{1%tsp} (2 tsp for 4 servings), and juice from one lemon wedge (two wedges for 4). Season with salt and pepper.

> Swap in broccoli for potatoes; roast 12-15 minutes.

In a second medium bowl, combine @mayonnaise{4%tbsp}, @Dijon mustard{4%tsp}, scallion whites, juice from one lemon wedge (two wedges for 4 servings), and @hot sauce{1%tsp} to taste.

In a third medium bowl, whisk together @tempura batter{82%g}, @garlic powder{1%tsp}, remaining Old Bay seasoning, @cold water{1/3%cup} (2/3 cup for 4), and a big pinch of salt. (TIP: If mixture is too thick, add more water 1 TBSP at a time until it reaches a pancake-batter-like consistency.) Stir mushrooms into batter until fully coated.

Heat a 1/3-inch layer of oil in a #large pan{} over medium-high heat. Once oil is hot enough that a drop of batter sizzles when added to the pan, use #tongs{} to add coated mushrooms in a single layer. TIP: Work in batches if necessary.

Cook until golden brown, ~{3-4%minutes} on first side and ~{1-2%minutes} on second side. Using a #slotted spoon{}, transfer mushrooms to a paper-towel-lined #plate{}. Season with salt.

While mushrooms cook, halve @demi-baguettes{2} lengthwise, stopping before you get all the way through.

Toast, cut sides up (place directly on oven rack or use a baking sheet), until golden brown, ~{3-5%minutes}.

Spread cut sides of baguettes with spicy remoulade; fill with mushrooms, @sliced dill pickle{1} slices, and as much slaw as you like.

Divide sandwiches and fries between plates. Serve with any remaining slaw, any remaining remoulade, and remaining lemon wedges on the side. TIP: If you've got some on hand, serve ketchup or malt vinegar with your fries!